DEB packaging managment   
Command                         Description                                                      
------------------------------- ------------------------------------------------------------------
dpkg -i <pkg>.deb               Install a local .deb package.                                    
dpkg -r <pkg>                   Remove a package (leaves config files).                          
dpkg -P <pkg>                   Purge a package (removes config files too).                      
dpkg -l                         List all installed packages.                                     
dpkg -l <pattern>               List matching installed packages (dpkg -l '*ssh*').        
dpkg -s <pkg>                   Show status information about an installed package.              
dpkg -L <pkg>                   List all files installed by a package.                           
dpkg -S <file>                  Find which package owns a specific file.                         
dpkg --get-selections           Get a list of selected packages (can be used for backups).       
dpkg --set-selections           Restore package selections (used with --get-selections).         
dpkg -c <pkg>.deb               List contents of a .deb file (without installing).               
dpkg -I <pkg>.deb               Show metadata and headers from a .deb file.                      

Command                     Description                                                  
--------------------------- ------------------------------------------------------------ 
sudo apt update             Update package list from repositories (metadata only).       
sudo apt upgrade            Upgrade all installed packages to latest versions.           
sudo apt full-upgrade       Upgrade system intelligently (may remove obsolete packages). 
sudo apt install <pkg>      Install a package by name.                                   
sudo apt remove <pkg>       Remove a package, but keep config files.                     
sudo apt purge <pkg>        Remove a package along with its config files.                
sudo apt autoremove         Remove unused packages installed as dependencies.            
sudo apt search <keyword>   Search for packages related to keyword.                      
apt show <pkg>              Show detailed info about a package.                          
apt list --installed        List all installed packages.                                 
apt list --upgradable       List all packages that have updates available.               
dpkg -l                     List installed packages (from lower-level dpkg).             
dpkg -i <file.deb>          Install a .deb package manually.                              
dpkg -r <pkg>               Remove a package using dpkg.                                 
dpkg -P <pkg>               Purge (remove including config) via dpkg.                    
sudo apt clean              Remove downloaded .deb files from /var/cache/apt/archives.   
sudo apt autoclean          Remove outdated cached .deb files.                           
apt-cache search <keyword>      Search for packages matching a keyword (like apt search).        
apt-cache show <pkg>            Display detailed metadata for a package (description, deps).     
apt-cache policy <pkg>          Show installed and candidate versions, and repo priorities.      
apt-cache stats                 Show cache statistics (number of packages, structures, etc).     
apt-cache depends <pkg>         Show package dependencies.                                       
apt-cache rdepends <pkg>        Show reverse dependencies (who depends on this pkg).             
apt-cache dump                 Dump entire metadata cache (mostly used for debugging).           
apt-cache pkgnames              List all known package names (useful for scripts/tools).         



RPM packaging managment  
Command                              Description                                               
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
rpm -e <pkg>                         Remove an RPM package.                                            

Querying rpm information
# rpm -q --requires emacs-common    -q option: see information about the package.
# rpm -q --provides emacs-common
# rpm -q --scripts httpd
# rpm -qi <pkg>                    -qi: include descriptions.
# rpm -ql <pkg>                    -ql: list files
# rpm -qd <pkg>                    -qd: show documentation
# rpm -qc <pkg>                    -qc: show configuration files.



Managing RPM Packages with YUM
Yellowdog Updater Modified: YUM helped solve the managment dependencies with RPM packages:/etc/yum.conf
Software repositories can be enabled by dropping files ending in .repo into the directory: /etc/yum.repos.d/
Command                                      Description                                                                
------------------------------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
yum list available                           List all available packages from enabled repositories.                     
yum list installed                           List all currently installed packages.                                     
yum list all                                 List both installed and available packages.                                
yum search <keyword>                         Search for packages with a keyword in the name or description.             
yum info <pkg>                               Show detailed information about a specific package.                        
yum provides <file>                          Find which package provides a specific file or capability.                
yum deplist <pkg> | less                     List dependencies for a package and what provides them.                   
yum install <pkg>                            Install a package from enabled repositories.                               
yum reinstall <pkg>                          Reinstall a package (refresh to original state).                           
rpm -i --replacepkgs <pkg>-<ver>.rpm         Reinstall a specific .rpm file, overwriting existing installation.         
rpm -V <pkg>                                 Verify installed files against package metadata (size, checksum, perms).   
yum erase <pkg>                              Remove a package and any unused dependencies.                              
yum history                                  View yum transaction history (installs, upgrades, removals).               
yum check-update                             Check for available package updates.                                      
yum update                                   Install available updates for all packages.                                
yum grouplist | less                         List all available package groups.                                         
yum groupinfo <group>                        Show detailed information about a specific group.                          
yum groupinstall <group>                     Install all packages in a named group (Development Tools).           
yum groupremove <group>                      Remove a previously installed package group.   



Maintaining your RPM package database and cache.
Command                                Description                                                                
------------------------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
yum clean packages                    Remove downloaded .rpm package files from the cache.                       
yum clean metadata                    Remove repository metadata (forces fresh repo sync on next operation).     
yum clean all                         Clean all cached data: packages and metadata.                              
yum check                             Check RPM database for problems like missing dependencies or corrupt data. 
yum clean <pkg>                       Clean a specific cached package (if causing errors, rebuild cache entry).  



DNF High-level package manager vs RPM Low-level tool
Command                                Description                                                                
------------------------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
sudo dnf check-update                  Check for available updates.                              
sudo dnf update                        Download and install available updates.                   
sudo dnf upgrade                       Same as update (preferred in newer versions).             
sudo dnf install <pkg>                 Install a package.                                         
sudo dnf remove <pkg>                  Remove a package.                                          
sudo dnf reinstall <pkg>               Reinstall a package.                                       
sudo dnf search <keyword>              Search for packages matching a keyword.                   
dnf info <pkg>                         Show detailed info about a package.                       
dnf list installed                     List all installed packages.                               
dnf list available                     List all available packages.                               
sudo dnf group list                    Show available package groups (like "Development Tools"). 
sudo dnf group install "<group>"       Install a group of related packages.                       
sudo dnf group remove "<group>"        Remove a group of packages.                                
sudo dnf clean all                     Clean all cached files.                                    
sudo dnf autoremove                    Remove packages no longer needed.                         
sudo dnf history                       View the history of package installs/removals.            
sudo dnf downgrade <pkg>               Revert to an older version of a package.      



Zypper packaging managment  
Command                                Description                                                   
----------------------------------- ----------------------------------------------------------------
sudo zypper refresh                    Refresh repository metadata (equivalent to apt update).         
sudo zypper update                     Update all packages to latest versions.                         
sudo zypper dup                        Perform distribution upgrade (switch to newer repo versions).   
sudo zypper install <pkg>              Install a package.                                               
sudo zypper remove <pkg>               Remove a package.                                                
sudo zypper search <keyword>           Search for packages by name or description.                      
zypper info <pkg>                      Show detailed info about a package.                              
zypper list-updates                    List packages with available updates.                            
zypper list-patches                    List available patches for the system.                           
sudo zypper patch                      Apply all available patches.                                     
zypper repos                           Show configured repositories.                                    
sudo zypper addrepo <url> <name>       Add a new repository.                                             
sudo zypper removerepo <name>          Remove a repository.                                              
zypper packages                        List installed packages from all repositories.                   
zypper ps                              List processes using deleted files (post-update helper).         
sudo zypper clean                      Clean up cached data.                                             
sudo zypper verify                     Check for broken/missing dependencies.                           


NMCLI Commands (NetworkManager CLI) BONUS!!!!
Command                                 Description                                                       
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
nmcli                                   Show general status of NetworkManager.                            
nmcli device status                     Show status of all network devices.                               
nmcli connection show                   List all saved network connections.                               
nmcli device show <device>              Display detailed info about a specific device.                    
nmcli connection show <name>            Show details of a specific connection profile.                    
nmcli connection up <name>              Activate a network connection by name.                            
nmcli connection down <name>            Deactivate a network connection by name.                          
nmcli device connect <device>           Connect a specific device.                                        
nmcli device disconnect <device>        Disconnect a specific device.                                     
nmcli connection add ...                Add a new connection (manual config, see examples below).         
nmcli connection delete <name>          Delete a saved network connection.                                
nmcli radio wifi off                    Turn off Wi-Fi radio.                                             
nmcli radio wifi on                     Turn on Wi-Fi radio.                                              
nmcli networking off                    Disable all networking (airplane mode).                           
nmcli networking on                     Enable all networking.                                            
nmcli device wifi list                  Scan and list available Wi-Fi networks.                           
nmcli device wifi connect <SSID>        Connet to a Wi-Fi network (may prompt for password).             
nmcli connection modify <name> ...      Modify settings of an existing connection.                        




                      






